Article V
(iii) the expiry date of any requested Letter of Credit is (A) more than two years after the date of Issuance, unless the Required Banks and such Issuing Bank have approved such expiry date in writing, or (B) after the date which is seven days prior to the scheduled Maturity Date (unless the Company confirms in writing to such Issuing Bank and the Administrative Agent, at the time of the Issuance that would cause the expiry date of such Letter of Credit to be after such seventh preceding day, that such Letter of Credit will be a Supported Letter of Credit on the scheduled Maturity Date and such Letter of Credit is in fact a Supported Letter of Credit on the scheduled Maturity Date, in which case such expiration date shall not be later than one year after the scheduled Maturity Date);
(iv) any requested Letter of Credit is not in a form reasonably acceptable to such Issuing Bank, or the Issuance of a Letter of Credit shall violate any applicable policy of such Issuing Bank;
(v) such Letter of Credit is in a face amount less than $250,000 (or a lesser amount acceptable to the Administrative Agent and such Issuing Bank), or to be denominated in a currency other than Dollars or an Offshore Currency; or
(vi) a default of any Bank's obligations to fund under exists or any Bank is at such time a Defaulting Bank, unless such Issuing Bank has entered into satisfactory arrangements with the Company or such Bank to eliminate such Issuing Bank's risk with respect to such Bank.
